    "what_description": "Ceropegia schoenlandiana is a succulent plant species belonging to the family Apocynaceae. It has a climbing habit, with stems up to 1.5 meters long and 2-3 centimeters in diameter, covered with fine, white or brown hairs. The leaves are fleshy, lanceolate to elliptical in shape, and measure 4-9 centimeters long by 1-2 centimeters wide, with a prominent midrib and a short petiole. The inflorescence is a dense spike, up to 15 centimeters long, with funnel-shaped flowers that are 4-5 centimeters long and 2-3 centimeters wide, with a five-lobed corolla and a yellow or orange throat surrounded by a red or reddish-brown rim. The flowers are highly fragrant, emitting a sweet, honey-like scent at night, attracting pollinators like hawk moths and bats.",
